# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: heligoland-bight
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] Ameland is, counted from the west, the fourth inhabited Dutch Wadden island and belongs to the Friesland (*Fryslân*) province.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] The whole island falls under one municipality, which carries the same name.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] The Wadden islands form the border between the North Sea and the Wadden Sea, which lies on the south side of the island file.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] The municipality of Ameland had a population of 3,746 in 2021.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] The island has four villages, and one small part-village.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] There were two other villages: Sier and Oerd.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] Sier was buried by advancing sand dunes, with the last house being abandoned around 1730, and Oerd was flooded in the first half of the 18th century.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] The names of these villages live on in MS *Oerd* and MS *Sier*, which are the names of the ferries to the island.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] First mentioned as Ambla in the 8th century, it paid tribute to the county of Holland until in 1424 its lord, Ritske Jelmera, declared it a "free lordship" (*vrijheerschap*): the Lordship of Ameland.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] Although Holland, Friesland and the Holy Roman Emperor contested this quasi-independent status, it remained a free lordship until the ruling family, Cammingha, died out in 1708.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] After that, the Frisian stadtholder John William Friso, Prince of Orange, became lord of Ameland and after him, his son the stadtholder of all the Netherlands, William IV, Prince of Orange, and his grandson, William V, Prince of Orange.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] Only in the constitution of 1813 was the island finally integrated into the Netherlands into the province of Friesland.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] The monarchy of the Netherlands still maintain the title *Vrijheer van Ameland* today.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] In 1871–72, a dike was built between Ameland and the mainland by a society for the reclamation of Frisian land from the sea.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] The dike ran from Holwert to Buren and was 8.7 km (5 mi) long.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] The province and the Dutch realm each paid 200,000 guilders.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] In the end, it was unsuccessful; the dike did not prove to be durable and in 1882, after heavy storms in the winter, repairs and maintenance of the dam were stopped.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] The dike can still be partially seen at low tide.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] The dam at Holwert is the beginning of this dike.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] In 1940, German troops were ferried to the island and within hours Ameland was under the control of the German Army.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] Due to its limited military value, the Allies never invaded Ameland.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] The German forces on the island did not surrender until 2 June 1945, almost a full month after the defeat of Nazi Germany.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] In July 2023, a fire on the Panamanian flagged cargo ship MV *Fremantle Highway* carrying over 3,700 cars off the coast of Ameland left one sailor dead and 22 others injured.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] Like all West and East Frisian Islands, Ameland is a unique piece of nature.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] The profusion of different plants on the island is caused by the immense variety of landscapes.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] One of the scenic areas is the **Oerd**, a large complex of dunes which is still expanding by the year.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] Because of the differing landscapes and types of flora, over 60 different species of birds are sitting there every year.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] At the eastern part of the Oerd lies a beach plain called the Hon.
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] Besides dunes and beaches, Ameland has some woods, like the *Nesser bos* ("Wood of Nes").
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] Most travelers reach the island by ferry from Holwert on the mainland of Friesland, but there is also an airport near Ballum (Ameland Airport).
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] A bus service connects the ferries from Hollum/Ballum (route 130) and Buren/Nes (route 132).
[src:heligoland-bight/ameland] When the sea between Friesland and Ameland is at low tide, one can walk across (see mudflat hiking).
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The island is made up of a sandy core of geestland and features an extended beach all along its west coast, facing the open North Sea.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The east coast borders to mudflats of the Wadden Sea.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Sand dunes are a characteristic part of Amrum's landscape, resulting in a vegetation that is largely made up of heath and shrubs.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The island's only forest was planted in 1948.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Amrum is a refuge for many species of birds and a number of marine mammals including the grey seal and harbour porpoise.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Settlements on Amrum have been traced back to the Neolithic period when the area was still a part of the mainland of the Jutland peninsula.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] During the Middle Ages, Frisian settlers arrived at Amrum and engaged in salt making and seafaring.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] A part of the modern population still speaks Öömrang, a dialect of the North Frisian language, and Frisian traditions are kept alive.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] With the island hosting many endangered species of plants and animals, its soil being largely unproductive for agriculture and as a popular seaside resort in general, Amrum's population today almost exclusively lives from the tourism industry.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Amrum's area measures 20.4 km2, making it the tenth-largest island of Germany (excluding Usedom which is partly Polish territory).
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Including the large Kniepsand beach on the western shore to the surface area results in a total area of c.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Amrum's surface area has however been subject to constant change due to land loss and gain caused by the sea.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] During the 19th century, a 20th part of the area recorded in the beginning of the century had been lost, but in 1913, a net gain was again recorded at the Kniepsand.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Amrum is one of three isles with a geestland core in Nordfriesland.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] This sandy core is made up of glacial deposits from the Saalian glacial period.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] To the east, it borders to the Wadden Sea mudflats of the North Sea.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The east side is also where the island's historic hamlets are situated: Norddorf, Nebel, Süddorf and Steenodde.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] On the geestland core, one can find extended areas of heath and woodland which form a strip that runs along a north-south line on the axis.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] West of this woodland strip, a region of 838 hectares (2,070 acres) is covered with dunes that run all along the island for about 12 km.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The maximal width of this area amounts to more than a kilometre.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Amrum's tallest dune near Norddorf is called *a Siatler* (the settling dune); it reaches 32 m in height.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Northward, the dune area extends into a small peninsula called *Odde*.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] In the south of Amrum, the newest settlement, Wittdün, is located.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] West of the dunes, the entire shore of Amrum is made up of the *Kniepsand* beach; it counts among northern Europe's largest sand beaches.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] North of Norddorf there is some marshland, another small marsh area can be found between Süddorf and Steenodde.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Both of them are protected from the sea by dikes.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] During low tide it is possible to reach the neighbouring island of Föhr by mudflat hiking.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Amrum's population amounts to about 2,300 and the island is divided into three municipalities: Norddorf, Nebel and Wittdün.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The northernmost settlement is the seaside resort of Norddorf with a decoy pond and a sector light.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Amrum's largest village, Nebel, is located near the eastern coastline.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Notable sights there include the church of St.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Clement with its "talking gravestones", the *Öömrang Hüs* - a museum of local history, a wind mill and the Cemetery of the Homeless.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Süddorf, today a district of Nebel, is the island's oldest hamlet.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Steenodde, also a neighbourhood of Nebel, had long been Amrum's only port until Wittdün, founded 1890, had taken over as the island's major ferry terminal.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Of the three municipalities, Wittdün is most clearly influenced by tourism.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The oldest traces of settlements in the area date back to the Neolithic with a number of dolmens among them.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Also many tomb sites from the Bronze and Iron Ages have been preserved.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] In the dunes west of the decoy pond, the remainders of an Iron Age hamlet have been found.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] It is unknown whether the Ambrones, who together with the Cimbri and Teutones threatened Rome around 100 BC, stemmed from this island which back then was still connected to the mainland by a land bridge.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] In the early Middle Ages the island was colonised by the Frisians.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The oldest known record of Amrum island has been found in the *Danish Census Book* of King Valdemar II of Denmark from 1231.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Next to salt making, agriculture, fishery and whaling, merchant shipping was one of the main sources of income for a long time.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Hark Olufs, a sailor from Süddorf who had been enslaved by Algerians in 1724, advanced to the rank of a General until he was allowed to return to his native island in 1736.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] During the late 19th century, tourism became a rapidly emerging business on Amrum and effectively changed the island's economy.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] During the Middle Ages, Amrum, as well as all of North Frisia proper, belonged to the so-called *Uthlande*, the Outer Lands, which only successively became parts of the Danish realm or the Duchy of Schleswig.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] After the conflicts between the Danish kings and the counts of Schauenburg about the rule over Schleswig, Amrum and western Föhr became an enclave of Denmark and contrary to neighbouring areas, it was not any longer a part of the Duchy of Schleswig.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] This state endured until 1864, when Denmark lost Schleswig to Prussia after the Second Schleswig War.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] For a brief period after that war, Amrum was ruled together by Prussia and Austria, yet in 1867 the island came under Prussian rule and was made a part of the province of Schleswig-Holstein.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] At first, Amrum formed a municipality within the district of Tondern.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] In 1920, the Schleswig Plebiscites resulted in a clear majority vote for Amrum staying with Germany, while Tondern fell back to Denmark.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Until 1972, Amrum belonged to the *Südtondern* district which then merged into the newly created district of Nordfriesland.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] During the 19th century, Amrum still had a considerably lower population than today.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Church records from 1821 to 1833 show an average population of 587, a census in 1860 noted 642 inhabitants, and in 1871, the population had dropped to 571.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Among other factors, the decrease owed to the fact that large parts of Amrum's population had emigrated — mainly to the United States.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Today, more people with ancestors from Amrum live in the United States than there are on Amrum proper, and the connections between Amrum and the U.S. are still being cultivated.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Eventually, tourism began only to flourish on the island when a seaside resort was established in Wittdün in 1890, which also led to a rapid increase in population.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] On 29 October 1998, the cargo ship *Pallas* ran aground off Amrum, causing a severe oil spill in the region.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The North Frisian language in the Öömrang dialect is spoken by roughly a third of the population.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Those 800 Amrumers are all multilingual.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Due to the isolated location of the islands, the North Frisian dialects developed so differently, that *Öömrang* can be understood by people from Föhr, yet is hardly recognisable for those from Sylt or mainland Nordfriesland.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Many Amrumers moreover speak Low German, since it had been the language of the coastal sailors.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Only a few people speak the Danish language.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Amrum's national costume for girls and women is coloured black and white and is amply decorated with silver ornaments.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] It is mostly worn on confirmation services or at tourist events.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] There are two peculiar traditions on Amrum.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] On February 21 the *Biakendai* is celebrated, where a great bonfire is lit to dispel winter.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] On the occasion, people blacken each other's faces with soot.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The festival originates from the old liturgical holiday of Cathedra Petri, which was originally celebrated on February 22.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The custom is also popular in other North Frisian municipalities.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] On New Year's Eve the *Hulken* takes place, where groups of mostly young people dress up in costumes and walk from house to house to let others guess their true identity (similar to Halloween).
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Depending on their age, they are either treated with sweets or alcoholic drinks.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Amrum's main branch of economy is tourism.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] In 2007 the island could provide 12,000 beds.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] In 2008 approximately 135,000 tourists and 1.3 million lodgings were registered.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Agriculture is also being practised on Amrum and the port hosts a single fisherman.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The local newspaper is called *Der Insel-Bote* (The Island Courier) and published by the Schleswig-Holsteinischer Zeitungsverlag.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] It is the common paper for both Föhr and Amrum.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Moreover, Amrum was the set for many German cinematic and TV films, e.g.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The island is connected by ferry services to neighbouring Föhr and to the mainland at the harbour of Dagebüll.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] During the summer season, a fast passenger boat offers services between the ports of Hörnum on Sylt, the Hallig Hooge and the harbour of Strucklahnungshörn on Nordstrand.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Amrum's terminal is located at Wittdün, the ferries are operated by *Wyker Dampfschiffs-Reederei GmbH (W.D.R.)*.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Most tourists will reach Amrum via Dagebüll.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] From there, the ferry journey takes 90 minutes on a straight route, but the more usual route via a stop at Wyk auf Föhr takes 120 minutes.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The ferry service to the Halligen and the mainland terminal of Schlüttsiel was terminated in 2019 because the port of Schlüttsiel has become too silted up for extended traffic.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] On the island, the bicycle is the main means of transport next to cars; compared to other areas of Germany, Amrum provides an excellent network of bicycle routes.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Numerous bicycle rental services exist for tourists.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] A bus service connects Norddorf, Nebel and Wittdün on an hourly schedule (every 30 minutes during the summer season).
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Like the ferries, the bus service is operated by W.D.R.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] A less common form of transport is mudflat hiking between Amrum and Föhr.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] From 1893 to 1939, a railway service was operated on Amrum.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] There is no airstrip on the island because any plans to establish one have so far vehemently been opposed.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Plants and wild animals on Amrum are marked by the proximity to the sea, but some also distinguish themselves by extreme rarity and a high ecological value worth of protection.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] This fact was acknowledged by the establishment of two nature reserves and Amrum's proximity to the Schleswig-Holstein Wadden Sea National Park.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Amrum's vegetation is determined by the sea and by the different types of landscapes on the island, most of which are low in nutrients.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] In parts of the dune belt and on the *Kniepsand* marram grass or sea wormwood grow, as well as numerous other sand-loving plants like sheep's bit which will bloom in sheltered areas between the dunes.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Also some stunted pines, bent by the sea wind, and *Salix repens*, the creeping willow can be found there.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Until the 1970s, the rare sea holly could still be seen in the dunes.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] East of there are heaths and conifer or mixed forests.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] In some dune slacks, peat bogs can be found which occasionally host the carnivorous plant common sundew.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The once abundant marsh gentian vanished during the 1990s.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The Amrum forest was mainly planted in 1948 on an area of heath.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Until then only a few forested regions could be found around the decoy ponds.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] With 180 hectares, Amrum has the largest ratio of forested land of all Germany's North Sea islands.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Mainly pines, firs and birches can be found here.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Meanwhile, the forest has largely lost its artificial nature.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] So one will encounter numerous plants on all levels and many species of fungi.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The "geestland", east of the forest, is mostly used for farming.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Its grassland grows plants such as Harebell (*Campanula rotundifolia*), Sea Thrift (*Armeria maritima*) and Carthusian Pink (*Dianthus carthusianorum*) and several species of hawkweed.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] In the small marshlands, some sedges and the ragged robin may be seen.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Here is the most nutritious soil on Amrum.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Even the soil of Amrum's gardens is so low in nutrients that only a few sorts of plants, e.g. hollyhock, will grow there without fertilising.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] On the salt marshes along the eastern shore of Amrum, many salt-tolerant species can be found.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Pioneer plants such as *Salicornia europaea* and alkali grasses, grow on and stabilize the mudflats.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Like the vegetation, Amrum's wildlife is determined by the island's location within the North Sea.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Thus there are only a few species of wild mammals on Amrum, such as hares, mice, hedgehogs and bats.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] In the 12th century, rabbits were introduced as game.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] A few years ago a pregnant vixen was set free on Amrum.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] She and her offspring caused severe damage to the island's fauna, but since then they have been hunted down.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] In the sea and on the sand bars off Amrum, thus within the National Park, harbour seals, grey seals and harbour porpoises have their habitats.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Occasionally in December and January, young grey seals are washed ashore on Amrum's beaches due to storm surges and are thereafter nursed by the adults.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Amrum counts among the most important hatching areas for seabirds in Germany.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Since the dunes of Amrum are a protected nature reserve, they are the only dunes along the west coast of Schleswig-Holstein where seagulls and ducks breed.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] In other dune areas of the North Sea coast these birds are usually scared off by tourists.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Additionally vast flocks of migratory birds will rest on Amrum during the season, e.g. red knot, brent goose or sanderling, all of whom are able to find sufficient food along the coasts of Amrum.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Moreover, a number of songbirds can be found and pheasants which were equally introduced as game are common.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Lizards and amphibians, such as moor frog, natterjack toad and smooth newt are other examples of land vertebrata.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] In the sea surrounding Amrum numerous fish species typical of the North Sea can be found, like plaice and atlantic herring.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] A 1940 report mentioned several worms like Nematodes, Archiannelida, Oligochaeta and Turbellaria, crustaceans like ostracods, and ciliate protozoans in the sands of the Kniepsand beach.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Since the 1980s, the abundance of harbour porpoises in the sea off Amrum and Sylt has been increasing and a protected marine area was created in 1999 to provide shelter for them.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The number of other marine species is equally great, the hermit crab, the common whelk, and the lugworm are all among them.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] Of them, mainly the sand shrimps are commercially used by "harvesting" them from the seabed with cutters.
[src:heligoland-bight/amrum] The shrimps are then sold as *Nordsee-Krabben* ("crabs"), which — though in strict taxonomical terms a misnomer — is their traditional culinary name along the German coast.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] It is located in the middle of the island chain known as the East Frisian Islands (German: *Ostfriesische Inseln*) and is the smallest permanently inhabited island in the chain according to the area and number of inhabitants.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The gat or tidal channel of Wichter Ee in the west separates Baltrum from Norderney and the tidal creek Accumer Ee in the east separates it from Langeoog.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] There are two villages on the island – *Ostdorf* (English: Eastern village) and *Westdorf* (English: Western village) – although they have essentially merged into one.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The ferry for Baltrum departs from the small port near the village of Neßmersiel (in the parish of Dornum) with connection to the train station of Norden.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The island has its own ferry terminal and a small airstrip.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The island is about 5 kilometres (3.1 mi) long and 1.5 kilometres (0.93 mi) wide.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] It covers an area of 6.5 square kilometres (2.5 sq mi) and has a population of around 600 people, swelling to about 3,500 during the summer months due to tourism.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Tourists (mainly from the Ruhr Area in North Rhine-Westphalia) travel to Baltrum to enjoy the countryside of the Lower Saxony Wadden Sea National Park, the beach and attractions such as the indoor swimming pool filled with sea water or a miniature golf course.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The highest point on the island is a central coastal dune with a viewing platform on top called *Aussichtsdüne* in German and is 19.3 metres (63 ft) above sea-level.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The origin of the name *Baltrum* is not clearly clarified.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] In 1398, the island was mentioned for the first time in a document of enfeoffment as *Balteringe* meaning either "pasture" or "[the place of] the sons or followers of Balter" in Old Frisian.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Another assumption is that the name is derived from the Norse god Baldr – son of Odin and Frigg.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] In the recent past an ironic version arose, one would be *bald 'rum* (English: soon around) when encircling the island, as the island is small it would not take a long time to walk around Baltrum.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Nevertheless, the circumference amounts to about 15 kilometres (9.3 mi).
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The geographers Strabo and Pliny the Elder provide an indication that the island existed since the first century BC and AD.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] During the era of the East Frisian chieftains, from 1350 to 1464, the East Frisian islands belonged to the powerful family tom Brok.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] In 1398 Baltrum was mentioned in a document for the first time, when Widzel tom Brok assigned *Balteringe* (besides the other islands) to Duke Albert I of Bavaria and received them back as fief.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] In the 17th century Baltrum had an elongated shape similar to the present shape of the barrier islands Norderney and Juist.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Through the centuries Baltrum lost a huge amount of land at its west coast due to wind and sea conditions which the extension at the east coast could not compensate.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Between 1650 and 1960 the island moved about 5 kilometres (3.1 mi) at its west side to east, whereas the east coast moved only 1.5 kilometres (0.93 mi) to east.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] A journey from a committee in 1650 reports that the 14 inhabitants on the island of that time were in jeopardy by the sea.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] In 1737 there was a village with a church which had to be abandoned due to silting of shifting sand dunes in 1800.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The new village, named Western village, was settled down around 800 metres (2,600 ft) to the west of the present day west coast (near the present day shoal Othelloplate in-between Baltrum and Norderney) and in the east there was the Eastern village.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] A storm surge in 1825 disrupted the island in several pieces and it became mostly uninhabitable, followed by deserting the Western village.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] From 1870 onwards the island was protected against the power of the sea with groynes, wooden palisades and revetments.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Furthermore, are levees protecting the built-up area against floodings.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] On the island exist no official street names but house numbers, instead.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Currently (retrieved 2009), are about 300 numbers assigned to houses.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The numbering is based on the date of the house construction in ascending order.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] So the numbers reveal some history of the buildings on the island.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] However the numbers do not change if a building is replaced by a newer construction.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Although Baltrum became a seaside resort in 1876, the tourism grew very slowly.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Since 1966 Baltrum has been a seaside health resort approved by the state of Germany.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Two hotels were opened in the end of the 19th century, *Hotel Küper* in 1892 and *Hotel zur Post* in 1895.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Before the World War II broke out 5,000 to 6,000 people visited Baltrum annually.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] In 1960 nearly 17,000 tourists showed up and since the 1970s there are over 30,000 people making holidays every year during the peak season.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Besides the approximately 500 inhabitants about 3,000 guests are constantly living on the island during the peak seasons exhausting the acceptance capacity of the two small villages.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Baltrum is a completely car-free island, because of the traffic ban of all kind of motor vehicles.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The only exceptions are vehicles of the volunteer fire department, an ambulance, a few wheel loaders and some machines needed for the coastal protection.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] From 1949 until 1985 there was a small single track *Inselbahn Baltrum* (English: Baltrum Island Railway) which was an unelectrified narrow gauge railway for baggage and cargo transportation.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] No bicycle sharing system exists on Baltrum and the tourists are asked not to bring their own bicycles onto the island, riding bicycles is the privilege of inhabitants.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The passenger and freight transportation is accomplished by horse-drawn carriages.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The baggage is transported by two-wheeled or four-wheeled carts or also carriages, use of electrical bicycles is the latest trend.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] There are no street names on Baltrum, and postal addresses are related to the chronology of the development of the areas meaning that the numbering is geographically independent.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] There is a search and rescue station presently on Baltrum which is operated by the German Maritime Search and Rescue Service.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Baltrum is tidal independent laid by ferries owned by the shipping company *Baltrum Line*, founded in 1928, starting in Neßmersiel.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The journey takes about 30 minutes and depending on the season and tourist season one ferry leaves once up to four times for each direction daily.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The baggage is containerized and transported in the same ferry as the vacationers.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The highlights of the passage are the seals on the shoals ahead of Norderney passed by the ferry.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The shipping company manages a bus connection to the train station of Norden, Lower Saxony.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Until 2006 the freight traffic was accomplished with the ferry *Baltrum II* via the port in Norddeich, Lower Saxony, but since then is transacted via the port in Neßmersiel.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The port of Neßmersiel was inaugurated in 1970 and extended by a cargo wharf with 35 metres (115 ft) in length from April to August 2008 due to the relocation of the freight transportation.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The Baltrum Airfield (ICAO: EDWZ) is a small special-use airfield located on the East Frisian island of Baltrum in Lower Saxony, Germany, serving as an important transport link between the car-free island and the mainland.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Established in the early 1970s, the airfield developed alongside the growth of tourism and local infrastructure, with a paved runway completed in 2002 to improve operational reliability.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] The airfield features a single paved runway (09/27) measuring approximately 360 m in length and 15 m in width and lies only a few metres above sea level on the low-lying “Heller” area of the island, which can be affected by storm surges and high tides.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Due to its short runway and environmental restrictions, operations are limited primarily to light single-engine aircraft, motor gliders, ultralight aircraft, and helicopters.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] Scheduled and charter flights—most notably short connections to Norden-Norddeich—play a significant role in supplying residents and transporting visitors, making aviation an essential complement to ferry services for this remote North Sea community.
[src:heligoland-bight/baltrum] At the event of low water Baltrum is reachable from the port of Neßmersiel as a guided walk across the mudflats taking 2.5 hours.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The **Battle of Heligoland Bight** was the first Anglo-German naval battle of the First World War, fought on 28 August 1914, between ships of the United Kingdom and Germany.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The battle took place in the south-eastern North Sea, when the British attacked German patrols off the north-west German coast.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The German High Seas Fleet was in harbour on the north German coast while the British Grand Fleet was out in the northern North Sea.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Both sides engaged in long-distance sorties with cruisers and battlecruisers, with close reconnaissance of the area of sea near the German coast—the Heligoland Bight—by destroyer.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The British devised a plan to ambush German destroyers on their daily patrols.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] A British flotilla of 31 destroyers and two cruisers under Commodore Reginald Tyrwhitt, with submarines commanded by Commodore Roger Keyes, was dispatched.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] They were supported at longer range by an additional six light cruisers commanded by William Goodenough and five battlecruisers commanded by Vice Admiral David Beatty.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The British suffered casualties of 35 killed and 55 wounded; one light cruiser and three destroyers suffered damage.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Despite the disparity of the ships involved in the battle, the battle was regarded as a great victory in Britain, where the returning ships were met by cheering crowds.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Beatty was vaunted a hero, although he had taken little part in the action or planning of the raid, which was led by Commodore Tyrwhitt and conceived by him and Keyes, who had persuaded the Admiralty to adopt it.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The raid might have led to disaster, had the additional forces under Beatty not been sent by Admiral John Jellicoe at the last minute.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The German government, the Kaiser in particular, restricted the freedom of action of the German fleet, instructing it to avoid contact with superior forces for several months thereafter.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The battle took place less than a month after the British declaration of war against Germany on 5 August 1914.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The war on land led to defeat for the French and their Allies at the Battle of the Frontiers, the German invasion of Belgium and France.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] British naval tactics had typically involved a close blockade of ports and this had been the British plan for war against Germany up to 1913.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The Admiralty had realised that the advent of submarines armed with torpedoes and mines meant that operations involving capital ships near an opponent's ports would place them at great risk of surprise attack.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Ships would be obliged to keep moving and return to port every few days to refuel.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The German navy had expected that Britain would adopt its traditional approach and had invested in submarines and coast defences.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The main body of the German navy—the High Seas Fleet (HSF)—was outnumbered by the British Grand Fleet stationed around home waters and could not expect victory in a general fleet engagement.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The HSF adopted a strategy of waiting in defended home ports for opportunities to attack parts of the larger British force.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The British adopted a strategy of distant blockade, patrolling the North Sea rather than waters close to Germany.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Without access to the Atlantic, the German ships were contained in an area where they could not attack Allied merchant shipping.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] To keep the HSF in harbour, the Grand Fleet made occasional forays and patrolled with smaller cruiser and battlecruiser squadrons.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The bulk of the British Expeditionary Force (BEF) was transported to France between 12 and 21 August, protected by British destroyers and submarines patrolling Heligoland Bight, which German ships would have to cross if they sortied from their bases.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The Grand Fleet remained on patrol in the centre of the North Sea ready to move south but no attack came.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The German army had anticipated a rapid transfer of the British army to France, German naval planners overestimated the time the British would need and German submarines were on patrol seeking the Home Fleet.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] At Harwich, Commodore Roger Keyes commanded a squadron of long-range submarines that regularly patrolled the Heligoland Bight and Commodore Reginald Tyrwhitt commanded a destroyer patrol.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] They observed that German destroyers had adopted a regular pattern of patrols where each evening cruisers would escort destroyers out of harbour to patrol for British ships during the night before being met and escorted home each morning.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Keyes and Tyrwhitt proposed to send a superior force during darkness to ambush the German destroyers as they returned.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Three British submarines would surface in a position to draw the destroyers back out to sea while a larger British force of 31 destroyers accompanied by nine submarines would cut them off from Germany.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Other submarines would wait for any larger German ships leaving the Jade estuary to help.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Keyes impressed Winston Churchill, the First Lord of the Admiralty with the daring of his plan, which was adopted with some changes.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] An attack at 08:00 on the German daytime patrol was preferred.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Keyes and Tyrwhitt requested support for their operation, in particular bringing the Grand Fleet south and the support of the squadron of six light cruisers commanded by Commodore William Goodenough.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The attack was planned for 28 August; the submarines were to sail on 26 August, while Keyes would travel on the destroyer *Lurcher* and the surface ships would depart at dawn on 27 August.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Tyrwhitt, aboard the brand new light cruiser HMS *Arethusa*, would command the 3rd Flotilla of 16 modern *Laforey*-class destroyers, whilst his subordinate, Captain William Blunt, aboard the light cruiser HMS *Fearless*, would command the 1st Destroyer Flotilla of 16 older destroyers.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Tyrwhitt had requested the replacement of his cruiser HMS *Amethyst* because she was too slow to keep up with his destroyers but *Arethusa* did not arrive until 26 August.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Her crew was inexperienced and it was discovered that its new 4 in (102 mm) Mk V guns jammed when fired.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Admiral Sir John Jellicoe, commanding the Grand Fleet, was not told of the plan until 26 August.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Jellicoe immediately requested permission to send reinforcements to join the raid and to move the fleet closer to the action but was allowed only to send battlecruisers in support.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Jellicoe dispatched Vice Admiral David Beatty with the battlecruisers HMS *Lion*, *Queen Mary* and *Princess Royal*; Goodenough, with the 1st Light Cruiser Squadron, comprising the light cruisers HMS *Southampton*, *Birmingham*, *Falmouth*, *Liverpool*, *Lowestoft* and *Nottingham*.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Jellicoe sailed south from Scapa Flow with the remainder of the fleet.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Jellicoe sent a message advising Tyrwhitt that he should expect reinforcements but the signal was delayed at Harwich and never received.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Tyrwhitt did not discover the additional forces until Goodenough's ships appeared through the mist, leading to a certain apprehension because he was expecting to meet only German vessels.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The E-class submarines HMS *E4*, *E5* and *E9* were ordered to attack reinforcing or retreating German vessels.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] HMS *E6*, *E7* and *E8* were positioned 4 mi (3.5 nmi; 6.4 km) further out to draw the German destroyers out to sea.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] HMS *D2* and *D8* were stationed off the river Ems to attack reinforcements should they come from that direction.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] At around 07:00, *Arethusa*, steaming south towards the anticipated position of the German ships, sighted a German torpedo boat, *G194*.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Accompanying *Arethusa* were the 16 destroyers of the 3rd Destroyer Flotilla.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] 2 mi (1.7 nmi; 3.2 km) behind were *Fearless* with the 1st Destroyer Flotilla of 16 destroyers and 8 mi (7.0 nmi; 13 km) behind them was Goodenough with the six cruisers; visibility was no more than 3 mi (2.6 nmi; 4.8 km).
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] *G194* immediately turned towards Heligoland, sending wireless reports Rear Admiral Leberecht Maass, commander of the German destroyer squadron.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Maass informed Rear Admiral Franz von Hipper, responsible for local defence and commander of the German battlecruiser squadron.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Hipper was unaware of the scale of the attack but ordered the light cruisers SMS *Stettin* and *Frauenlob* to defend the destroyers.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The light cruisers SMS *Mainz* moored on the Ems, SMS *Strassburg*, *Cöln*, *Ariadne*, *Stralsund* and *Kolberg* from the river Jade, *Danzig* and *München* from Brunsbüttelkoog on the river Elbe were ordered to raise steam.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Tyrwhitt ordered four destroyers to attack *G194* and the sound of gunfire alerted the remaining German destroyers moving north, that turned south towards home.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Before they could complete the turn, they were sighted by British destroyers which commenced firing.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The trailing destroyer *V1* was hit, followed by the destroyer-minesweepers *D8* and *T33*.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] *G9* called for fire against the attacking ships from coastal artillery but the mist meant the gunners could not tell which ships were which.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] At 07:26, Tyrwhitt turned east, to follow the sound of gunfire sighting ten German destroyers, which he chased through the increasing mist for 30 minutes, until the ships reached Heligoland and he was forced to turn away.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] At 07:58, *Stettin* and *Frauenlob* arrived, reversing the situation so that the British destroyers were obliged to retreat towards *Arethusa* and *Fearless*.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] *Stettin* withdrew, since the German destroyers had escaped but *Frauenlob* was engaged by *Arethusa*.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] *Arethusa* was better armed but two of its four 4 in (102 mm) guns jammed and another was damaged by fire.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] *Frauenlob* — armed with ten 10.5 cm (4.1 in) guns — caused considerable damage before a shell from one of *Arethusa*'s two 6 in (152 mm) guns destroyed her bridge, killing 37 men including the captain, forcing her to withdraw and return to Wilhelmshaven badly damaged.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] At 08:12, Tyrwhitt returned to the original plan to sweep the area from east to west.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Six returning German destroyers were sighted which turned to flee, when *V187* turned back.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The German ship had seen two cruisers, *Nottingham* and *Lowestoft* from Goodenough's squadron ahead and tried to pass through the British destroyers by surprise, only to be surrounded by eight destroyers and sunk.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] As British ships began to rescue survivors from the water, the German light cruiser *Stettin* approached and opened fire, forcing the British to abandon the rescue, leaving behind British sailors.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The British submarine *E4* had observed the action and launched a torpedo at *Stettin* but missed; *Stettin* attempted to ram the submarine, which dived to escape.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] When *E4* resurfaced the larger ships had gone and the submarine rescued the British crewmen afloat in small boats with the German survivors.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The Germans were left behind with a compass and direction toward the mainland as the submarine was too small to take them.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] At 08:15, Keyes—with *Lurcher* and another destroyer—sighted two four-funnelled cruisers.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Still unaware that additional British ships were involved, he signalled *Invincible* that he was chasing two German cruisers.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Goodenough received the signal, abandoned his search for enemy vessels to attack and steamed to assist Keyes against his own ships, *Lowestoft* and *Nottingham*.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Keyes, being chased by four more German cruisers, attempted to lure them towards *Invincible* and *New Zealand*, reporting them as enemy ships.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Eventually, Keyes recognised *Southampton* and the ships attempted to rejoin Tyrwhitt.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The British submarines were still unaware that the other ships were present and at 09:30, a British submarine fired two torpedoes at *Southampton*; the submarine missed and then escaped when *Southampton* tried to ram it.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] *Lowestoft* and *Nottingham* remained out of communication range; separated from the rest of their squadron, they took no further part in the action.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Tyrwhitt turned to assist Keyes, on receipt of the signal that he was being chased, sighted *Stettin* but lost her in the mist before coming upon *Fearless* and her destroyer squadron.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] *Arethusa* was badly damaged and at 10:17 *Fearless* came alongside and both cruisers were stopped for twenty minutes while repairs were made to the boilers.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Beatty had been following the events by radio 40 mi (35 nmi; 64 km) to the north-west.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] By 11:35, the British ships had still not completed their mission and withdrawn; with the rising tide, larger German ships would be able to leave harbour and join the engagement.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Beatty took his five battlecruisers south-eastwards at maximum speed, an hour away from the engagement.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] While the advantages of using his more powerful ships to rescue the others was clear, this had to be weighed against the possibility of mischance by torpedo or of meeting German dreadnoughts once the tide was up.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] At 11:30, Tyrwhitt's squadron came upon the German cruiser *Mainz* and the ships engaged for 20 minutes, before the arrival of Goodenough caused *Mainz* to attempt an escape.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Goodenough gave chase and in trying to lose him, *Mainz* came back across the path of *Arethusa* and her destroyers.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Her steering was damaged, causing her to turn back into the path of Goodenough's ships and she was hit by shells and a torpedo.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] At 12:20, her captain ordered his ship to be scuttled and the crew to abandon ship.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Keyes had now joined the main body of ships and brought *Lurcher* alongside *Mainz* to take off the crew.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Three British destroyers had been seriously damaged in the engagement.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] *Strassburg* and *Cöln* attacked together but the battle was interrupted by Beatty and the battlecruisers.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Attempts to rescue the crew were interrupted by the arrival of a submarine; one survivor was rescued by a German ship two days later, out of some 250 men who had survived the sinking.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Rear Admiral Maass perished with his ship.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Four German cruisers survived the engagement, saved by the mist.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] *Strassburg* nearly approached the battlecruisers but saw them in time and turned away.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] She had four funnels, like the British Town-class cruisers, which caused sufficient confusion to allow her time to disappear into the mist.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The German battlecruisers *Moltke* and *Von der Tann* left the Jade at 14:10 and began a cautious search for other ships.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Rear Admiral Hipper arrived in *Seydlitz* at 15:10 but by then the battle was over.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] To preserve his ships the Kaiser determined that the fleet should, "hold itself back and avoid actions which can lead to greater losses".
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Admiral Hugo von Pohl, Chief of the German Naval Staff, wired Ingenohl that, "in his anxiety to preserve the fleet [William] ... wished you to wire for his consent before entering a decisive action".
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The Germans had assumed that their cruisers, leaving port one by one, would not meet larger ships or a superior force and failed to keep their ships together so they might have better odds in any engagement.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Beatty—when faced with the choice of leaving one of his ships to finish off disabled enemies—had elected to keep his squadron together and only later return in force to finish off the ships.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Goodenough managed to lose track of two cruisers, which played no further part in the battle.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] German light cruisers armed with larger numbers of faster firing 10.5 cm (4.1 in) guns, proved inferior to similar British cruisers with fewer but more powerful 6 in (15 cm) guns.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The German ships proved difficult to sink despite severe damage and impressed the British with the quality of their firing.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] British and German sources reported the determination and bravery of the defeated German ships when overwhelmed.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] No one reported the presence of British cruisers to Admiral Hipper until 14:35.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Had he known, he could have brought his battlecruisers to sea faster and consolidated his fleet, possibly preventing German losses and instead inflicting some on the departing British ships.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The British operation took longer than anticipated and large German ships would have had sufficient high water to join the battle.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The British side suffered from poor communication, with ships failing to report engagement with the enemy to each other.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The initial failure to include Jellicoe in planning the raid could have led to disaster, had he not sent reinforcements and the communication failures meant British ships were unaware of the new arrivals and could have attacked them.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] There was no way to warn off British submarines which might have targeted their own ships.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] It had been the decision of Admiral Sturdee—Admiralty Chief of Staff—not to inform Jellicoe and also not to send additional larger ships which had originally been requested by Keyes.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Jellicoe had countermanded this decision once he knew of the raid, by sending ships which were part of his command.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Keyes was disappointed that the opportunity for greater success had been lost by not including the additional cruisers properly into the plan as he had originally intended.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Jellicoe was disturbed by the Admiralty's failure to discuss the raid with their commander in chief of the Home Fleet at sea.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The Germans appreciated that standing patrols by destroyers wasted time and resources, leaving them open to attack.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The Germans sowed defensive minefields to prevent enemy ships from approaching and freed the destroyers to escort larger ships, which were never to be sent out one by one.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The British realised it was foolish to have sent *Arethusa* into battle with inadequate training and jammed guns.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] British ships were criticised for having fired considerable ammunition and torpedoes with little effect but this criticism backfired when at the Battle of Dogger Bank in 1915, British crews tried to conserve ammunition and missed opportunities to damage German vessels.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] Germany lost the light cruisers *Mainz*, *Cöln* and *Ariadne* and the destroyer *V187* sunk.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The light cruisers *Frauenlob*, *Strassburg* and *Stettin* had been damaged and returned to base with casualties.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] German casualties were 1,242 with 712 men killed, including Maass and the destroyer commodore.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The British took 336 prisoners, 224 German sailors were rescued by Commodore Keyes on the destroyer *Lurcher* and brought to England, the son of Tirpitz being among the prisoners.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-heligoland-1914] The British had lost no ships and casualties did not exceed 35 men killed and about 40 wounded.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The **Battle of the Heligoland Bight** was the first "named" air battle of the Second World War, which began the longest air campaign of the war on 3 September 1939, the Defence of the Reich.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] After the declaration of war, RAF Bomber Command began operations against Nazi Germany but limited their attacks to those targets that were purely military and had little risk of civilian casualties.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] This largely limited their efforts to attacks on the *Kriegsmarine* (German Navy) warships in German ports to prevent their use in the Battle of the Atlantic.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Early operations led the RAF to conclude that fighter aircraft were not a serious threat against modern bombers.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] They were also marked by a lack of coordination and minor issues such as bad weather and communication problems that meant none of these early operations were very intense.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The RAF implemented changes to ensure more aircraft could be launched more rapidly to make up for these issues.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] On 18 December 1939, a force of three squadrons was launched against capital ships anchored in the Wilhelmshaven area.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Originally 24 Vickers Wellingtons took off, but two turned back due to engine trouble before reaching German airspace.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The German reaction was slow, but eventually between 80 and 120 fighter aircraft were launched, although only 44 made contact with the British bombers.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Of the 22 bombers that reached the target area, the Luftwaffe shot down 12, over half the force.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The battle had a huge influence on both sides' strategies.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] It led the RAF to abandon daylight missions in favour of night bombing as daytime casualties were too high.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] In contrast, the failure of the raid led the Luftwaffe to believe Germany proper was invulnerable to enemy attack.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] This belief was reinforced by the success of the Battle of France, which meant that opposing air forces were pushed too far away for effective bombing attacks on the German homeland.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The Germans' neglect of their day fighter force had serious strategic consequences in later years.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] By the time they began reorganising defences to combat continued RAF raids and also the United States Army Air Forces (USAAF) strategic bombing campaign, they were already engaged in a war of attrition for which they were not prepared.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] This oversight was one of the contributing factors in the defeat of the Luftwaffe in the Defence of the Reich campaign.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The Battle of the Heligoland Bight was later described as "amongst the most important actions of the entire war".
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The RAF lacked a four-engine bomber with adequate defensive protection which could carry heavy bomb loads to German targets.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The only possible targets within range of British bombers were those in the industrial region of the Ruhr.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The Netherlands and Belgium wished to remain neutral and refused to allow the RAF to establish bases from which they could fly deeper into Germany.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] They also forbade overflying by British bombers to and from Germany.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] After the outbreak of war, the French refused to allow RAF bombers to bomb German cities from French airfields.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The French felt secure behind the Maginot Line but their air force did not possess the modern bombers to attack the Luftwaffe.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] French fighter forces were not yet ready for an all out defensive campaign against the Germans either.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] A fear of retaliation was the main French reason.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The only recourse was to fly missions directly from Britain and only ports or coastal cities in northern Germany were within easy reach.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] This state of affairs suited the British, in particular, the Admiralty.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The most immediate threat to the Allies during the Phoney War period was the U-boat.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Some German submarines had been sent to sea before the British declaration of war.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Once war was declared, the U-boats began operations against British ships that were bringing in supplies from North America and areas of the British Empire.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] German submarine *U-47* sank the battleship HMS *Royal Oak* at Scapa Flow in October 1939, with the loss of 786 crew.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] As a consequence the Admiralty pressed for the RAF to concentrate its efforts on RAF Coastal Command rather than a strategic bomber force.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] This was debated within the British establishment well into 1941.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] To avoid the bombing of civilian targets, the British formulated the Western Air Plan 7B (WAP 7B), which planned for attacks on German warships.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] German ships were legitimate targets and, at sea or in port, were far enough away from civilian areas to avoid unnecessary casualties.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The Plan revolved around their elimination to prevent their use as supplements to the U-boat fleet.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] To fit in with this strategy, the initial plans of the RAF involved raids against German shipping on receipt of the results of aerial reconnaissance.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] This was attempted on 3 September, when a Bristol Blenheim (flown by Flying Officer Andrew McPherson of No.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] 139 Squadron RAF)—on a reconnaissance flight over the North Sea—spotted a large naval force in the Schillig Roads off Wilhelmshaven.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The radio failed and an attack could not be launched until McPherson returned to base, when 15 Handley Page Hampdens and nine Vickers Wellington bombers were sent against the German ships.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The weather was poor and the bombers failed to find any targets.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] A similar attempt was made on 4 September, when McPherson again spotted warships off Brunsbüttel, Wilhelmshaven and in the Schillig Roads.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The radio failed again and no attack could be launched until McPherson's return.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] 107 Squadron RAF along with five more from No.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] 139 Squadron and eight Wellingtons of No.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] 149 Squadron RAF took off to locate the German warships *Gneisenau*, *Scharnhorst* and *Admiral Scheer*, which some aircraft found.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] At least one of the crews—Flying Officer (F/O) Bill McRae—nearly took off without a bomb load; looking in, he noticed the bomb bay was empty.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] On the way to the target, Squadron Leader Paul Harris ordered his gunners to test their weapons.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] They all failed and he was heading into German territory defenceless.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Not wanting to turn back on his first raid, he pressed ahead.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The same targets were attacked by 9 Squadron later in the day, in and around Brunsbüttel.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Results were poor with five Blenheims and two Wellingtons lost and only minimal damage caused to the German warships.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] *Admiral Scheer* was hit by three bombs that failed to explode, while the light cruiser *Emden*—not one of the priority targets—was present and also damaged by a Blenheim that crashed into the forecastle of the ship.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The crash killed 11 sailors and injured 30.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] One Wellington bomber accidentally strayed over Danish territory and dropped five bombs on the town of Esbjerg, mistaking it for Brunsbüttel; one bomb hit an apartment block, killing one and wounding seven.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The accidental bombing led to false rumors that British forces had occupied Southern Jutland.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] *Gruppe* of JG 77; II Wing, Fighter Group 77, *Oberstleutnant* Carl-August Schumacher) took off from Nordholz Airbase and intercepted 9 Squadron.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] *Feldwebel*s Hans Troitzsch and Alfred Held each claimed a victory and *Leutnant* Metz another.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] 9 Squadron were the first RAF aircraft to be shot down by enemy fighters during the war and Troitzsch was most likely to have been the first enemy pilot to shoot one down.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] 107 Squadron were shot down by anti-aircraft fire.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The Germans believed their air defences had established an effective defence from Allied attack.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Use of the early Freya radar had given the German fighters eight minutes warning of their approach.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The delay between spotting German warships and the arrival of the bombers was considered to be too great, and it was decided to carry out reconnaissance in force, with formations of bombers being sent out over the North Sea to find and attack German warships.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Their orders forbade them from attacking ships in port, infringing neutral airspace or even attacking German warships escorting merchant ships.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The German pilot shot down was future German ace Günther Specht.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] He was shot down by Corporal Copley of No.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The German ships were the *Brummer* and the minesweeper *M1407* both sunk by unexploded bombs passing through the ship.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] A German report stated the attack was cleverly executed from out of the sun and delivered to avoid the nearby civilian areas.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] An armed reconnaissance by twelve Wellingtons on 14 December resulted in five being lost as the formation, at very low level because of the low cloud base, was engaged by fighter aircraft and anti-aircraft guns.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The RAF believed that none of the lost Wellingtons had been shot down by fighters and so maintained faith in their defensive capabilities when flown in tight formations.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] This summation was odd considering that several of the surviving bombers had damage from small-arms fire.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The Luftwaffe claimed five bombers for the loss of one fighter while none of the German *FlaK* units claimed a victory.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The Luftwaffe's air defence organisation went through a number of changes in the first months of the war.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The defence of the northern German ports and vital strategic targets was given to the local or nearest *Luftverteidigungskommando* (Air Defence Command).
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] In this case the unit responsible for the protection of German warships of the *Kriegsmarine* was the *Luftverteidigungskommando Hamburg* (Air Defence Command Hamburg).
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The system was impractical; the Hamburg air defence district controlled air and ground defences but each was geographically in no position to help the other.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] There was no combined arms synthesis, meaning that the *FlaK* arm did not directly support the German defences thereby forming one mass defence.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Instead, fighter units protecting the coast were held there, with *Kriegsmarine* *FlaK* units, while the Hamburg air defence artillery was held too far inland.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The Luftwaffe fighters and *FlaK* units were located too far apart to coordinate.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Coordination was not helped by the poor relations between the Luftwaffe and *Kriegsmarine* Commanders-in-Chief, *Reichsmarschall* Hermann Göring and *Großadmiral* (Grand Admiral) Erich Raeder.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The system required both services to work together but it produced co-operation difficulties.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Fighter units defending the North Sea coast were subordinated to *Luftgaukommando* XI (Air District Command 11) in Hanover.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] These fighter units would function as an autonomous fighter command or *Jagdfliegerführer* (Fighter Flyer Leaders).
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The command of Fighter Command unit was given to *Oberstleutnant* Carl-August Schumacher, a former commander of II./*Jagdgeschwader* 77.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Schumacher had served in the *Kaiserliche Marine* (Imperial German Navy) during the First World War and as an officer cadet had seen combat at the Battle of Jutland.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] It was hoped with his naval background and easy personality it would ease any difficulties with naval service cooperation.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Schumacher and his counterpart in the Navy were of the same rank, so each lacked authority over the other, an arrangement that stifled unity of command.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Schumacher was given a new command, Stab./*Jagdgeschwader* 1 (Command./Fighter Group 1, or JG 1), sometimes referred to as JG Nord (Fighter Group North) or JG Schumacher.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] In addition to the Bf 109D and E variants, the force was also equipped with the Messerschmitt Bf 110.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The lack of action during the Phoney War period meant that these aircraft, usually in demand by offensive air fleets (*Luftflotte*), were available for defensive roles.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Usually the group consisted of 9 Squadron, 37 Squadron, 38 Squadron, 99 Squadron, 115 Squadron, 149 Squadron together with 214 Squadron and 21 Squadron in reserve.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The Group was hastily set up for daylight missions, having been intended for night bombing.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The quality of the training was dubious and many of the crews had not been given proper tuition in formation flying.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Only 9 and 214 squadrons were able to fly in perfect formations.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] To improve formation flying and give crews experience of combat conditions, 37 Squadron practised mock combats with RAF Fighter Command Supermarine Spitfires from RAF Tangmere.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Warnings were given by the Spitfire pilots that they could have decimated the squadron within ten minutes because of their poor formation flying and lack of fighter escort but were ignored.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Squadron Leader Harris of 149 Squadron and Wing Commander Kellett were the only experienced combat leaders but Kellett had not flown with 9 or 37 Squadrons as a group and had never had a chance to practice formation flying or bombing with them.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] He had not been given the time or opportunity to discuss or formulate a plan for bombing naval targets, whether as a group, squadron or even as flights.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Nor had he even been able to discuss or pass on any tactical advice about what the formation should do in the event of fighter attack.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] He was given command of an incoherent group of squadrons which were highly inexperienced.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] For the 18 December mission, 24 Wellington Bombers from 9, 37 and 149 Squadrons were given to Kellet.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The British bombers flew in a diamond shape formation.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] On the morning of 18 December 1939, *The Times* of London published the story of the Battle of the River Plate and the demise of *Admiral Graf Spee* and a few hours later RAF Bomber Command attempted to sink another major warship.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] 60 of 17 December, the targets were German warships either in port or at sea.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The RAF bombers were ordered to overfly the Heligoland Bight and the port of Wilhelmshaven, attacking ships but avoiding civilian living quarters, merchant shipping or land itself.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The first Wellington, N2960, took off from RAF Mildenhall in Suffolk at 09:27 with Wing Commander Richard Kellett at the controls; 9 Squadron took off from the nearby RAF Honington, formed up over King's Lynn and started out over the North Sea.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] 37 Squadron took off but missed the rendezvous and caught up with the main formation an hour later over the North Sea.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Once over the Wash it set a course of 040° true, as far as latitude 55° north.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The plan was to avoid heavy anti-aircraft artillery concentrations on the Frisian Islands.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] As the formation left England the cloud broke and it found itself without cover in a bright, crystal-clear sky.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] N2984 and N2894, piloted by Duguid and Kelly, turned back; the first due to engine trouble, the other escorting the troubled bomber back to base.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The remaining bombers flew north past the Frisian Islands then turned due south, continuing their mission in perfect visibility which made it easy to be spotted by German aircraft.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Reaching the German–Danish border at 55°N 05°E, the formation turned south.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] It headed towards Schleswig-Holstein and then planned to turn due west to Wilhelmshaven.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The move was designed to initiate the attack from the east, through the "back door".
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The plan worked, as the bombers arrived without being intercepted but the southward journey caused the bombers to fly within range of a Freya on the island of Wangerooge.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] *Leutnant* Hermann Diehl of Regiment 3, battery LN-Vers was demonstrating the Freya set to a visiting naval officer.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Diehl was using Falck's 2./ZG 76 as a suitable target test the set.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] After some demonstration, he swung the set north, pointing to the Heligoland Bight.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] As soon as he did so he picked up an echo.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] He telephoned Schumacher's *Geschwader* at Jever.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] They were told that the naval radar reported nothing and that it was ridiculous to think the British would attack in such clear skies.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Diehl spoke to von *Major* Harry von Bülow-Bothkamp, commanding II./JG 77.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] No one wanted to listen; about 20 minutes later, naval Freyas also picked up the formation but still no fighters were scrambled.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] German radar was just as efficient as its British counterpart, the problem lay in communication.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The Luftwaffe and *Kriegsmarine* had poor communication and their areas of responsibility overlapped, creating confusion over who was responsible.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Added to this was the German disbelief that RAF would expose itself on a day when conditions favoured the fighter.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Only when observers on the ground confirmed that the formation existed were fighters scrambled.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The observers described a formation of 44 British aircraft, twice its actual strength.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] As the bombers passed down the coast, anti-aircraft artillery fire from ships and harbour defences was noted.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Once in the target area they also came under heavy anti-aircraft artillery fire from Bremerhaven and Wilhelmshaven.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Ships near Schillig Roads also opened fire.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The bombers replied with their machine guns to throw the gunners off.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] German fire was at the correct height but exploded behind the bombers.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Soon after, the formation was over Wilhelmshaven harbour, with *Gneisenau* and *Scharnhorst* at anchor beneath them.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The ships were too close to shore and Kellett chose not to risk dropping bombs to avoid civilian casualties.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Kellett—commanding the formation—had been ordered to attack at minimum altitude (about 10,000 ft (3,000 m)).
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The belief that the greatest danger would come from anti-aircraft fire, not German fighters, had by then become part of RAF operational doctrine.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] It was only at this point that fighters started to be scrambled to intercept the bombers.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Bülow-Bothkamp stated that it was the naval Freya that gave the alert, but this contradicts Diehl's account.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The first air engagement occurred an hour after the Luftwaffe Freya made the initial report.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] At 13:10, the RAF formation flew over the mud flats to the west of Cuxhaven and Wesermünde and came under fire from flak positions 214, 244 and 264.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] As Kellett turned west towards the Jade Estuary and over Wilhelmshaven anti-aircraft units 212, 222, 252, 262 and 272 opened fire.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] *Scharnhorst*, *Gneisenau* and all the other naval ships in the dock opened fire in support.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] In the distance, at Schillig Point, the bombers could see German fighters taking off from a camouflaged airstrip.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] In a quick briefing, the JG 1 commander had told his pilots to make a beam attack as it was a blind spot for the Wellington.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] A stern attack was dangerous, as the gunners could then target an attacking fighter with a coordinated and concentrated cone of fire.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] One weakness also noted was that early types of Wellingtons lacked self-sealing fuel tanks.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] This meant if the German fighters hit the wings, the bomber was liable to burn.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Unworried by the Luftwaffe, 149 Squadron was the only section to drop bombs on the ships in Wilhelmshaven harbour.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Six 500 lb (230 kg) bombs fell and the results were unknown.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] It was all the RAF had to show for its first major raid on a German target.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] As the bombers emerged from the anti-aircraft barrage, the RAF formation was disorganised.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Kellett's and Harris's formations were intact, but Squadron Leader Guthrie was ahead of his No.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Its commander, Squadron Leader Hue-Williams, was struggling to catch up with the main formation and was forging ahead of his formation without keeping it together.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Other members of Hue-Williams's squadron increased their speed to keep up with their leader.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Among the German claimants was Helmut Lent who was credited with two victories.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] After landing at Jever from a patrol, Lent took off to intercept.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] He engaged Herbie Ruse's Wellington, killing most of the crew.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The Wellington was pouring black smoke and Lent broke off believing it about to crash.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Lent then pursued Thompson's Wellington, which crashed just off the coast of Borkum.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Lent's third claim was not granted: he attacked and shot down Wimberley's aircraft but because the aircraft was already badly damaged and judged to be about to crash, Lent was refused the victory and Stab./JG 1's *Geschwaderkommodore* Schumacher was given the credit.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Schumacher also shot down Pilot Officer Lewis's aircraft, close to Borkum.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] At 13:45, the German fighters—at the limit of their endurance—returned to base.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] By 14:05, the other bomber formation was beyond interception range and the last shots were fired.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The German fighter crews claimed 38 bombers shot down, against actual RAF losses of 12 aircraft.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The gunners in the British bombers claimed twelve German fighters and twelve severely damaged.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] German casualties amounted to three Bf 109s destroyed, two severely damaged and two Bf 110s severely damaged, a case of overclaiming by both sides.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Seven Bf 110s and one Bf 109 suffered light damage.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Johann Fuhrmann and Roman Stiegler were the only pilots to die in this action; Dietrich Robitzsch from *Jagdgruppe* 101, wrote-off a Bf 109 but was uninjured; *Feldwebel* Hans Troitzsch (Bf 109) and *Leutnant* Gustav Uellenbeck (Bf 110) were wounded.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] British aircrews also claimed between sixty and eighty fighters engaging in combat over the Heligoland Bight.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] To back up their claims, the Luftwaffe insisted that 44 bombers were in the air, which was later increased by OKL to 52.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Some hours later these claims were reduced to 34 but months later the reports were analysed and reduced to 27 "confirmed" victories.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] This was still over twice the number that was shot down and five more than the size of the formation.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] German historians have claimed that official British figures were tampered with to hide losses but careful examination of the records reveals no deception.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Obituaries from the Commonwealth War Graves Commission record the identity of all service personnel who died during the war and have no known grave; as would be the case for airmen lost at sea.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] No airmen were reported missing that day from squadrons other than 9, 37 and 149.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The tactical assessment of both sides was radically different.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Bomber Command believed the attack was a failure as a result of poor formation flying and leadership.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] It was also maintained that better beam defensive armament and self-sealing fuel tanks were needed.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] These tactical considerations might, it believed, still salvage the day-bomber concept.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] On 19 December 1939, Air Vice-Marshal Jackie Baldwin reported that Guthrie and Hue-Williams were to blame for racing ahead of their formations and breaking up the defensive formation.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Baldwin sent his report to the Bomber Command Commander-in-Chief, Edgar Ludlow-Hewitt, who replied on 23 December and joined Baldwin in condemning the leaders of 9 and 37 Squadrons for abandoning their flight.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Hewitt called this action an "unforgivable crime", although Harris later stated that this was unfair, as Guthrie and Hue-Williams were untrained and had never faced the enemy before.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Harris also blamed 3 Group Headquarters, stating that there had been no planning or liaison between the squadrons.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Harris also noted the Group Operations Staff had not provided any formation lessons.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Even so, the notes also pointed to the importance of holding a formation within the section.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] If a section leader endeavoured to follow the formation leader (Wing Commander Kellet) to the detriment of their section, the formation would break apart.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Bomber formations were built on the idea of mutual protection, so if the formation came apart, each bomber would have to fend for itself, which would enable an enemy to pick off the bombers one by one.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Guthrie and Hue-Williams did not heed this advice; Kellett had followed the notes and he lost only one aircraft.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Harris had also kept his formation together and lost no Wellingtons.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Within a few weeks, a debate began on shifting air attacks to the cover of darkness, with Hewitt favouring this alternative.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Another issue that was raised by the mission was the lack of useful bombsights.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] At the time, the RAF was using the Course Setting Bomb Sight (CSBS), originally developed in World War I for aircraft flying at much lower speeds against poorly defended targets.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] He requested a new design that required a shorter time to settle and would allow maneuvering throughout the bomb run.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] This requirement led to the Mark XIV bomb sight, which was the RAF standard from 1942 on.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The German report also regarded the attempt by the RAF to attack in clear conditions and perfect visibility at altitudes of 10,000–16,000 ft (3,000–4,900 m) as "criminal folly".
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Schumacher stated that anti-aircraft fire proved effective at breaking up formations and damaging bombers which provided better opportunities for the fighter pilots.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] After the recent Polish Campaign, the German Army staff analysis had been rigorous in its analysis of that battle.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The Army General Staff had assessed the problems of leadership, tactics, command and control to improve effectiveness.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] It appears that Schumacher's fighter units did not do the same and were too busy congratulating themselves on their success.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Little evidence exists that the Luftwaffe took anything like the Army's approach in Poland, following its own victory at Heligoland Bight.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The historian for the Luftwaffe General Staff noted it was only exploited for propaganda, despite the operational problems and warnings the battle had flagged for attacker and defender.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The progress of the war from September 1939 to the summer of 1941, with a few exceptions, seemed to validate the Luftwaffe's pre-war focus on the offensive use of its fighter arm.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The success of the Luftwaffe in the Norwegian Campaign and the battles of the Netherlands, Belgium, France, Yugoslavia, and Greece had vindicated this method.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The Luftwaffe had defended German airspace by driving away enemy air power from Germany's borders and defeating its enemies in its own skies.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The occupation of its opponent's territory denied Germany's enemies the bases to attack German targets by air.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] German daylight defences were rarely tested during this time.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] This run of events and the knowledge that the RAF was capable of only short penetrations over France in daylight led the Luftwaffe to believe that Germany was invulnerable to attack.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] To maintain the offensive on the front line, bomber production dominated the air industry while the production of fighters was given less priority.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] By the time Germany declared war on the United States, on 11 December 1941, the failure of Operation Barbarossa meant the Luftwaffe's method of concentrating all its resources on the front line was failing.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The RAF began its campaign of night bombing in early 1940 and by mid-August 1942, the United States Army Air Forces (USAAF) entered the air war in force.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Even so, the OKL continued to resist sending its forces to defend Germany and weakening the front lines.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] It was only in May 1942—when the Luftwaffe faced the USAAF for the first time in daylight engagements and the commencement of USAAF 8th Air Force bombing raids on occupied Europe—that the danger of Allied strategic bombing by day gave the OKL cause for concern.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Even by the end of 1942, the measures taken to strengthen daylight anti-aircraft defences remained piecemeal and counterproductive.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Hans Jeschonnek summed up the attitude of the OKL when he stated that the Luftwaffe could deal with the Western Allies' daylight raids with "one" fighter wing.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] The events of 1943–1944 would prove this assumption wrong.
[src:heligoland-bight/battle-of-the-heligoland-bight-1939] Adolf Galland—*General der Jagdflieger* (General of the Fighter Force), 1941–1945—gave lack of organisation and of planning for air defence as one of the greatest mistakes made by the Luftwaffe during the war.
[src:heligoland-bight/bight-geography] In geography, a **bight** (/baɪt/) is a concave bend or curvature in a coastline, river or other geographical feature, or it may refer to a very open bay formed by such a feature.
[src:heligoland-bight/bight-geography] Such bays are typically broad, open, shallow and only slightly recessed.
[src:heligoland-bight/bight-geography] The size of bights differs greatly, which may be as small as a bend in a river or large like a sound.
[src:heligoland-bight/bight-geography] Traditionally, explorers defined a bight as a bay that could be sailed out of on a single tack in a square-rigged sailing vessel, regardless of the direction of the wind (typically meaning the apex of the bight is less than 25 degrees from the edges).
[src:heligoland-bight/bight-geography] According to the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea, an indentation with an area as large as (or larger than) that of the semi-circle whose diameter is a line drawn across the mouth of that indentation, can be regarded as a bay not merely a bight.
[src:heligoland-bight/bight-geography] The term is derived from Old English *byht* ("bend, angle, corner; bay, bight") with German *Bucht* and Danish *bugt* as cognates, both meaning "bay".
[src:heligoland-bight/bight-geography] Bight is not etymologically related to "bite" (Old English *bītan*).
[src:heligoland-bight/blauort] According to the Schleswig-Holstein National Park Office in Tönning, Blauort, like the sandbank of Tertius to the south, belongs to the parish of Hedwigenkoog.
[src:heligoland-bight/blauort] However, the state government of Schleswig-Holstein has not yet officially confirmed and authorised this.
[src:heligoland-bight/blauort] The islet of Blauort is migrating steadily eastwards, like all sandy islands on the west coast of Schleswig-Holstein.
[src:heligoland-bight/blauort] From 1938 to 1962, the sand moved towards the land at a rate of about 32 metres per year and, at present, it is about six miles from the coast.
[src:heligoland-bight/blauort] Blauort's highest point lies above the average high tide (which is about 1.83 m above sea level (NN) ) and is only completely submerged by spring tides or storm surges.
[src:heligoland-bight/blauort] Blauort is one of the few, largely unspoilt habitats on the coast and of great importance for seabirds and common seals, Since 1985 it has been part of protection zone *I* in the Schleswig-Holstein Wadden Sea National Park.
[src:heligoland-bight/blauort] Blauort is marked by a daymark, the *Blauortbake* ("Blauort daymark").
[src:heligoland-bight/blauort] In the summer months, guided mudflat walks of the *Blauortsand* are offered which depart from Büsum and Wesselburen.
[src:heligoland-bight/blauort] The Büsumer writer, Stefanie Bach Stein, called one of her books of poetry *Blauort*.
[src:heligoland-bight/heligoland-bight] The **Heligoland Bight**, also known as **Helgoland Bight**, (German: *Helgoländer Bucht*, pronounced [ˈhɛlɡoˌlɛndɐ ˈbʊxt]) is a bay which forms the southern part of the German Bight, itself a bay of the North Sea, located at the mouth of the Elbe river.
[src:heligoland-bight/heligoland-bight] The Heligoland Bight extends from the mouth of the Elbe to the islands of Heligoland and lies between the East Frisian island of Wangerooge and the North Frisian peninsula of Eiderstedt.
[src:heligoland-bight/heligoland-bight] The bight takes its name from the island of Heligoland.
[src:heligoland-bight/heligoland-bight] It was the location of World War I naval battles in 1914 and 1917.
[src:heligoland-bight/heligoland-bight] In 1939 it also had a World War II aerial battle named after it.
[src:heligoland-bight/heligoland-bight] In the Heligoland Basin (*Helgoländer Becken*), a basin lying directly southwest of Heligoland, the bight is up to 56 metres (184 ft) deep.
[src:heligoland-bight/heligoland-bight] One of the busiest shipping lanes in the world, from Hamburg and the mouth of the Elbe to the Straits of Dover and the English Channel, runs through the Heligoland Bight.
[src:heligoland-bight/heligoland-bight] The area also includes nature reserves such as the *Heligoland Felssockel* and the protected Wadden Sea, in which the Wadden Sea National Parks of Schleswig-Holstein (East), Hamburg (southeast) and Lower Saxony (south) are located.
[src:heligoland-bight/heligoland-bight] Besides the aforementioned islands of Heligoland, which form the northwestern boundary of the Heligoland Bight, there is the small island of Neuwerk in the southeast, which is located in the Wadden Sea off the Elbe estuary.
[src:heligoland-bight/heligoland-bight] South of this island is the estuary of the Weser and, to its west, the Jade Bight.
[src:heligoland-bight/heligoland-bight] Southwest of the Heligoland Bight is the East Frisian island of Wangerooge.
[src:heligoland-bight/heligoland-bight] East of the bight the Eider enters the sea with, to its north the Eiderstedt Peninsula and, to its south, Meldorf Bay.
